{"title_page": "William Byron (MP)", "text_new": "'''Hon. William Byron'''  (1749\u20131776) was a British politician who sat in the [[House of Commons]] from 1775 to 1776.\n\nByron was the son of [[William Byron, 5th Baron Byron]] and his wife Elizabeth Shaw, daughter of Charles Shaw of Besthorpe Hall, Norfolk, and was born on 27 October 1749.<ref name=Debrett>{{cite book|title=Debrett's Complete Peerage of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|author=Courthope, W.|date=1838|publisher=J. G. & F. Rivington|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_Ru4UAAAAQAAJ|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_Ru4UAAAAQAAJ/page/n328 258]|accessdate=6 November 2017}}</ref> He was educated at [[Eton College]] from 1763 to 1766.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1754-1790/member/byron-hon-william-1749-76 | title=BYRON, Hon. William (1749-76). | publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 1 November 2017}}</ref> In 1768 he was in France running up bills on his father's account.<ref>J. V. Beckett, (with Sheila Aley)  \"Byron and Newstead: The Aristocrat and the Abbey\" University of Delaware Press, 2001  p.59</ref>  His father was in serious financial difficulties which he hoped to resolve by obtaining a wealthy bride for William. However William eloped to Gretna Green with his cousin Juliana Elizabeth Byron, daughter of [[John Byron|Admiral John Byron]].<ref>J. V. Beckett, (with Sheila Aley)  \"Byron and Newstead: The Aristocrat and the Abbey\" University of Delaware Press, 2001 p. 66</ref>\n\nByron contested [[Morpeth (UK Parliament constituency)|Morpeth]] at the [[1774 British general election|1774 general election]]  on the Carlisle interest. He was defeated, but seated as [[Member of Parliament]] on petition on 28 January 1775. There is no record of any vote or speech by him in the eighteen months he was in Parliament.<ref name = HOP/>\n\nByron as heir was due to inherit the [[Baron Byron|Barony]], but he died on 22 June 1776.<ref name = HOP/> His son was killed by cannon fire in 1794 while fighting in [[Corsica]] and the barony ultimately went to the poet [[Lord Byron]].<ref name=Debrett/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Francis Eyre]]\n | before2 = [[Peter Delm\u00e9 (MP for Morpeth)|Peter Delm\u00e9]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Morpeth (UK Parliament constituency)|Morpeth]]\n | years =  1775\u20131776   \n | with  =  [[Peter Delm\u00e9 (MP for Morpeth)|Peter Delm\u00e9]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Gilbert Elliot-Murray-Kynynmound, 1st Earl of Minto|Gilbert Elliot]]\n | after2 = [[Peter Delm\u00e9 (MP for Morpeth)|Peter Delm\u00e9]]\n}}\n\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Byron, William}}\n[[Category:1749 births]]\n[[Category:1776 deaths]]\n[[Category:Eldest sons of barons]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1774\u20131780]]\n", "text_old": "'''Hon. William Byron'''  (1749\u20131776) was a British politician who sat in the [[House of Commons]] from 1775 to 1776.\n\nByron was the son of [[William Byron, 5th Baron Byron]] and his wife Elizabeth Shaw, daughter of Charles Shaw of Besthorpe Hall, Norfolk, and was born on 27 October 1749.<ref name=Debrett>{{cite book|title=Debrett's Complete Peerage of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|author=Courthope, W.|date=1838|publisher=J. G. & F. Rivington|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_Ru4UAAAAQAAJ|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_Ru4UAAAAQAAJ/page/n328 258]|accessdate=6 November 2017}}</ref> He was educated at [[Eton College]] from 1763 to 1766.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1754-1790/member/byron-hon-william-1749-76 | title=BYRON, Hon. William (1749-76). | publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 1 November 2017}}</ref> In 1768 he was in France running up bills on his father\u2019s account.<ref>J. V. Beckett, (with Sheila Aley)  \"Byron and Newstead: The Aristocrat and the Abbey\" University of Delaware Press, 2001  p.59</ref>  His father was in serious financial difficulties which he hoped to resolve by obtaining a wealthy bride for William. However William eloped to Gretna Green with his cousin Juliana Elizabeth Byron, daughter of [[John Byron|Admiral John Byron]].<ref>J. V. Beckett, (with Sheila Aley)  \"Byron and Newstead: The Aristocrat and the Abbey\" University of Delaware Press, 2001 p. 66</ref>\n\nByron contested [[Morpeth (UK Parliament constituency)|Morpeth]] at the [[1774 British general election|1774 general election]]  on the Carlisle interest. He was defeated, but seated as [[Member of Parliament]] on petition on 28 January 1775. There is no record of any vote or speech by him in the eighteen months he was in Parliament.<ref name = HOP/>\n\nByron as heir was due to inherit the [[Baron Byron|Barony]], but he died on 22 June 1776.<ref name = HOP/> His son was killed by cannon fire in 1794 while fighting in [[Corsica]] and the barony ultimately went to the poet [[Lord Byron]].<ref name=Debrett/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Francis Eyre]]\n | before2 = [[Peter Delm\u00e9 (MP for Morpeth)|Peter Delm\u00e9]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Morpeth (UK Parliament constituency)|Morpeth]]\n | years =  1775\u20131776   \n | with  =  [[Peter Delm\u00e9 (MP for Morpeth)|Peter Delm\u00e9]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Gilbert Elliot-Murray-Kynynmound, 1st Earl of Minto|Gilbert Elliot]]\n | after2 = [[Peter Delm\u00e9 (MP for Morpeth)|Peter Delm\u00e9]]\n}}\n\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Byron, William}}\n[[Category:1749 births]]\n[[Category:1776 deaths]]\n[[Category:Eldest sons of barons]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for Engl